5.1 Basic Components:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::

React Native does not use HTML or XML layouts.

Instead it provides cross-platform components that render native UI on:

Android

iOS

Example:

<View>
  <Text>Hello</Text>
</View>

React Native converts this to:

Android → TextView

iOS → UILabel



1️⃣ View Component:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::

View is the most fundamental component.

Think of it like:

| Technology | Equivalent                     |
| ---------- | ------------------------------ |
| Android    | `LinearLayout` / `FrameLayout` |
| Flutter    | `Container`                    |
| Web        | `div`                          |


View is used to contain other components and layout UI.

Example
import {View, Text} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){
  return(
    <View>
      <Text>Hello React Native</Text>
    </View>
  )
}

Styled View
<View style={{
  backgroundColor:'lightblue',
  padding:20
}}>
  <Text>Hello</Text>
</View>


2️⃣ Text Component:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Text displays text on the screen.

Important rule:

⚠️ Text must always be inside a Text component.

Wrong ❌

<View>
  Hello
</View>

Correct ✔

<Text>Hello</Text>
Example
<Text style={{fontSize:24}}>
  Welcome to React Native
</Text>
Nested Text
<Text>
  Hello <Text style={{fontWeight:'bold'}}>Ritesh</Text>
</Text>

Output:

Hello Ritesh

with bold text.


3️⃣ Image Component:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Image displays images.

Sources can be:

local images

remote URLs

Example (Remote Image)
import {Image} from 'react-native'

<Image
  source={{uri:'https://reactnative.dev/img/tiny_logo.png'}}
  style={{width:100, height:100}}
/>
Example (Local Image)

First place image inside project:

assets/logo.png

Then:

<Image
  source={require('./assets/logo.png')}
  style={{width:100, height:100}}
/>

Important:

React Native requires width and height for images


4️⃣ Button Component:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::

Button is used to trigger actions.

Example:

import {Button} from 'react-native'

<Button
  title="Click Me"
  onPress={() => console.log("Pressed")}
/>
Example With State
import React, {useState} from 'react'
import {View, Text, Button} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  const [count, setCount] = useState(0)

  return(

    <View>

      <Text>Count: {count}</Text>

      <Button
        title="Increase"
        onPress={()=> setCount(count+1)}
      />

    </View>

  )
}


5️⃣ TextInput Component:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

TextInput allows users to enter text.

Equivalent to:

| Technology | Equivalent  |
| ---------- | ----------- |
| Android    | `EditText`  |
| Flutter    | `TextField` |

Basic Example
import {TextInput} from 'react-native'

<TextInput
  placeholder="Enter your name"
/>
Controlled Input Example

import React, {useState} from 'react'
import {View, TextInput, Text} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  const [name, setName] = useState("")

  return(

    <View>

      <TextInput
        placeholder="Enter name"
        onChangeText={setName}
      />

      <Text>Hello {name}</Text>

    </View>

  )
}

When user types:

Ritesh

UI updates:

Hello Ritesh


5.2 Layout Components:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Mobile apps frequently display large amounts of content.

Example:

Products
Messages
Posts
Contacts
Notifications

React Native provides optimized components for these layouts.


1️⃣ ScrollView:- 
:::::::::::::::::::

ScrollView allows users to scroll vertically or horizontally through content.

Equivalent to:
| Technology | Equivalent              |
| ---------- | ----------------------- |
| Android    | `ScrollView`            |
| Flutter    | `SingleChildScrollView` |


Example
import React from 'react'
import {ScrollView, Text} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  return(

    <ScrollView>

      <Text style={{fontSize:30}}>Item 1</Text>
      <Text style={{fontSize:30}}>Item 2</Text>
      <Text style={{fontSize:30}}>Item 3</Text>
      <Text style={{fontSize:30}}>Item 4</Text>
      <Text style={{fontSize:30}}>Item 5</Text>

    </ScrollView>

  )
}

Users can scroll through the items.

Important Limitation

ScrollView renders all items at once.

Example:

1000 items → 1000 components rendered

This causes performance issues.

Therefore, ScrollView should only be used for small content lists.

Example use cases:

✔ Settings screen
✔ Profile screen
✔ Small forms


2️⃣ FlatList:- 
:::::::::::::::::::

FlatList is the most important list component in React Native.

It is designed for large datasets.

Unlike ScrollView, it uses lazy loading.

Only visible items are rendered

Equivalent to:

| Technology | Equivalent         |
| ---------- | ------------------ |
| Android    | `RecyclerView`     |
| Flutter    | `ListView.builder` |


Example Data
const data = [
  {id:'1', name:'Apple'},
  {id:'2', name:'Banana'},
  {id:'3', name:'Orange'}
]
FlatList Example
import React from 'react'
import {FlatList, Text, View} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  const data = [
    {id:'1', name:'Apple'},
    {id:'2', name:'Banana'},
    {id:'3', name:'Orange'}
  ]

  return(

    <FlatList
      data={data}

      renderItem={({item}) => (
        <Text style={{fontSize:24}}>
          {item.name}
        </Text>
      )}

      keyExtractor={(item) => item.id}
    />

  )
}


Important Props :- 

| Prop         | Purpose           |
| ------------ | ----------------- |
| data         | list data         |
| renderItem   | renders each item |
| keyExtractor | unique key        |
| horizontal   | horizontal list   |
| numColumns   | grid layout       |

Example Grid Layout
<FlatList
  data={data}
  numColumns={2}
  renderItem={({item}) => (
    <Text>{item.name}</Text>
  )}
/>


3️⃣ SectionList:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::

SectionList is used when list items are grouped into sections.

Example:

Contacts

A
 - Alex
 - Adam

B
 - Brian
 - Bella

Equivalent to:
| Technology | Equivalent             |
| ---------- | ---------------------- |
| Android    | Sectioned RecyclerView |
| Flutter    | ListView with groups   |


Example Data
const data = [
  {
    title:'Fruits',
    data:['Apple','Banana','Orange']
  },
  {
    title:'Vegetables',
    data:['Carrot','Potato','Tomato']
  }
]
SectionList Example
import React from 'react'
import {SectionList, Text, View} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  const sections = [
    {
      title:'Fruits',
      data:['Apple','Banana','Orange']
    },
    {
      title:'Vegetables',
      data:['Carrot','Potato','Tomato']
    }
  ]

  return(

    <SectionList

      sections={sections}

      renderItem={({item}) => (
        <Text style={{fontSize:20}}>
          {item}
        </Text>
      )}

      renderSectionHeader={({section}) => (
        <Text style={{fontSize:24, fontWeight:'bold'}}>
          {section.title}
        </Text>
      )}

      keyExtractor={(item, index) => index.toString()}

    />

  )
}

::::::::::::::
Comparison:- 
:::::::::::::::

| Component   | Best Use      |
| ----------- | ------------- |
| ScrollView  | small content |
| FlatList    | large lists   |
| SectionList | grouped lists |

5.3 Touch Handling:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

In mobile apps users interact with:

Buttons

Cards

Images

List items

Swipe gestures

React Native provides components to detect touch events.

Example interactions:

Tap
Long press
Double tap
Swipe
Drag


1️⃣ TouchableOpacity:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::

TouchableOpacity is one of the most commonly used touch components.

When pressed, it reduces opacity, giving a visual feedback effect.

Example
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, TouchableOpacity} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  const handlePress = () => {
    console.log("Button pressed")
  }

  return(

    <View style={{flex:1, justifyContent:'center', alignItems:'center'}}>

      <TouchableOpacity
        onPress={handlePress}
        style={{backgroundColor:'blue', padding:15}}
      >

        <Text style={{color:'white'}}>
          Press Me
        </Text>

      </TouchableOpacity>

    </View>

  )
}
What Happens

When user taps the button:

Opacity decreases
↓
onPress function executes

This creates a native button-like interaction.

TouchableOpacity Common Props
| Prop          | Purpose                    |
| ------------- | -------------------------- |
| onPress       | triggered on tap           |
| onLongPress   | triggered on long press    |
| activeOpacity | opacity value when pressed |


2️⃣ Pressable:- 
:::::::::::::::::::

Pressable is the modern replacement for Touchable components.

It provides more control over interaction states.

React Native now recommends Pressable for most cases.

Basic Example
import {Pressable, Text} from 'react-native'

<Pressable
  onPress={() => console.log("Pressed")}
>
  <Text>Press Here</Text>
</Pressable>
Press State Example

Pressable allows styling based on pressed state.

<Pressable
  onPress={()=> console.log("Pressed")}
  style={({pressed}) => ({
    backgroundColor: pressed ? 'gray' : 'blue',
    padding: 15
  })}
>

  <Text style={{color:'white'}}>
    Pressable Button
  </Text>

</Pressable>

Behavior:

Press
↓
background changes
↓
release
↓
action executed

Pressable Events

| Event       | Description           |
| ----------- | --------------------- |
| onPress     | tap                   |
| onLongPress | long press            |
| onPressIn   | finger touches screen |
| onPressOut  | finger leaves screen  |

3️⃣ Gesture Handling Basics:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Basic touch events include:

Tap
Long Press
Drag
Swipe

For simple gestures React Native uses Pressable / Touchable.

For complex gestures like:

swipe

pinch

drag

developers use gesture libraries such as:

React Native Gesture Handler

React Native Reanimated

These power advanced UI interactions in apps like:

Instagram

TikTok

Practical Example: Clickable Card
import React from 'react'
import {View, Text, Pressable} from 'react-native'

export default function App(){

  return(

    <View style={{flex:1, justifyContent:'center', alignItems:'center'}}>

      <Pressable
        onPress={()=> alert("Card clicked")}
        style={{
          padding:20,
          backgroundColor:'lightblue',
          borderRadius:10
        }}
      >

        <Text>
          Clickable Card
        </Text>

      </Pressable>

    </View>

  )
}

This pattern is used in:

Product cards
Profile cards
List items